{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16391"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16391"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.12,0.04,0,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116516"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9082"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16391"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98509"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5922"},{"type":"tags","id":"7116"},{"type":"tags","id":"7557"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21584"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116516"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset visual disturbance. Her medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia, managed with amlodipine and atorvastatin. On examination, her vital signs are stable. Formal perimetry demonstrates a visual field defect in the right lower quadrant of both eyes. Computed tomography of the brain reveals an acute infarct in the left parietal lobe.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the visual field defect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contralateral inferior quadrantanopia","Contralateral homonymous hemianopia","Bitemporal hemianopia","Monocular scotoma","Contralateral superior quadrantanopia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a \u003Cstrong\u003Econtralateral inferior quadrantanopia\u003C/strong\u003E due to a left parietal lobe infarct affecting the optic radiation. The anatomical arrangement of visual fibres in the optic radiation explains the pattern of visual field loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe superior portion of the optic radiation passes through the parietal lobe and carries information from the inferior visual field. The inferior portion (Meyer loop) curves through the temporal lobe and carries information from the superior visual field.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContralateral homonymous hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with complete interruption of the optic tract, lateral geniculate nucleus, or entire optic radiation. \u003Cstrong\u003EBitemporal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E results from chiasmal lesions affecting crossing fibres, typically from sellar masses. \u003Cstrong\u003EMonocular scotoma\u003C/strong\u003E affects only one eye and results from retinal or pre-chiasmal optic nerve pathology. \u003Cstrong\u003EContralateral superior quadrantanopia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with temporal lobe lesions affecting Meyer loop, not parietal lesions. The location of the lesion in the parietal lobe specifically affects fibres carrying information from the inferior visual field, resulting in a contralateral inferior quadrantanopia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A lesion in the parietal lobe optic radiation causes contralateral inferior quadrantanopia due to the anatomical arrangement of visual fibres.","Visual field defects follow predictable patterns based on the location of lesions along the visual pathway.","The Meyer loop of the optic radiation curves anteriorly in the temporal lobe before turning posteriorly to the occipital cortex."],"references":["Freddi TAL, Ottaiano AC. The Optic Nerve: Anatomy and Pathology. Semin Ultrasound CT MR. 2022 Oct;43(5):378-388. doi: 10.1053/j.sult.2022.04.006. Epub 2022 Apr 13. PMID: 36116850","Takahashi M, Goseki T, Ishikawa H, Hiroyasu G, Hirasawa K, Shoji N. Compressive Lesions of the Optic Chiasm: Subjective Symptoms and Visual Field Diagnostic Criteria. Neuroophthalmology. 2018 Sep 11;42(6):343-348. doi: 10.1080/01658107.2018.1438477. PMID: 30524487; PMCID: PMC6276958","Wall M. Perimetry and visual field defects. Handb Clin Neurol. 2021;178:51-77. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-12-821377-3.00003-9. PMID: 33832687","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98509"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16391"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98509"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T16:10:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9082"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116516"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11